292年","1280":"1280年","1306":"1306年","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"蘇格蘭音巴內-爾","Scotland":"英國蘇格蘭","Morayshire, Scotland":"蘇格蘭艾爾金爾","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"蘇格蘭艾爾金爾阿爾爾 豪斯","lifeSummary":"Margaret Comyn是William Comyn of Lochaber的女兒，於大約1265年出生。她於大約1291年與Sir Robert Comyn在蘇格蘭艾爾金爾結婚。他們至少是2個兒子的父母。她去世在英國蘇格蘭。"},"zh-hans":{"about 1265–":"大约1265年–殁","1265–Female":"1265年–殁","1261–1306":"1261年–1306年","1280–Male":"1280年–殁","1292–1365":"1292年–1365年","–Male":"殁","about 1280":"大约1280年","about 1291":"大约1291年","1365":"1365年","1265":"1265年","1261":"1261年","about 1265":"大约1265年","1292":"1292年","1280":"1280年","1306":"1306年","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"苏格兰音巴內-爾","Scotland":"英国苏格兰","Morayshire, Scotland":"苏格兰艾爾金爾","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"苏格兰艾爾金爾阿爾爾 豪斯","lifeSummary":"Margaret Comyn是William Comyn of Lochaber的女儿，于大约1265年出生。她于大约1291年与Sir Robert Comyn在苏格兰艾爾金爾结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。她去世在英国苏格兰。"},"hr":{"about 1265–":"oko 1265.–preminula","1265–Female":"1265–preminula","1261–1306":"1261–1306","1280–Male":"1280–preminuo","1292–1365":"1292.–1365","–Male":"preminuo","about 1280":"oko 1280.","about 1291":"oko 1291.","1365":"1365","1265":"1265","1261":"1261","about 1265":"oko 1265.","1292":"1292.","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Škotska, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotland","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"Altyre House, Elginshire, Scotland"},"cs":{"about 1265–":"okolo 1265–Zesnulá","1265–Female":"1265–Zesnulá","1261–1306":"1261–1306","1280–Male":"1280–Zesnulý","1292–1365":"1292–1365","–Male":"Zesnulý","about 1280":"okolo 1280","about 1291":"okolo 1291","1365":"1365","1265":"1265","1261":"1261","about 1265":"okolo 1265","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Skotsko, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotland","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"Altyre House, Elginshire, Scotland"},"da":{"about 1265–":"omkring 1265–Afdød","1265–Female":"1265–Afdød","1261–1306":"1261–1306","1280–Male":"1280–Afdød","1292–1365":"1292–1365","–Male":"Afdød","about 1280":"omkring 1280","about 1291":"omkring 1291","1365":"1365","1265":"1265","1261":"1261","about 1265":"omkring 1265","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Skotland","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"Altyre House, Elginshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1265–":"circa 1265–Overleden","1265–Female":"1265–Overleden","1261–1306":"1261–1306","1280–Male":"1280–Overleden","1292–1365":"1292–1365","–Male":"Overleden","about 1280":"circa 1280","about 1291":"circa 1291","1365":"1365","1265":"1265","1261":"1261","about 1265":"circa 1265","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Schotland","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"Altyre House, Elginshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1265–":"about 1265–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1261–1306":"1261–1306","1280–Male":"1280–Deceased","1292–1365":"1292–1365","–Male":"Deceased","about 1280":"about 1280","about 1291":"about 1291","1365":"1365","1265":"1265","1261":"1261","about 1265":"about 1265","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotland","Altyre House, Morayshire, Scotland":"Altyre House, Elginshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Comyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Irish:  see  Cumming  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cumming","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): most probably a habitational name from Bosc-Benard-Commin in Eure, France. This place lies on the edge of the Forêt de Rouvray, near Rouen, in the heart of the district from which came numerous Domesday barons, and so is much more likely to be the source of the name than Comines in Nord. The name is also possibly derived from the personal name <i>Cumin</i>, which is found in Norfolk, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th and 13th centuries and may be of Breton origin, according to Reaney. Compare Old Breton <i>Cunmin</i>, which also appears as <i>Cumin</i>, and is from <i>con-</i> ‘hound’ with an uncertain second element, perhaps the <i>min</i> ‘edge’ which is found in other personal names.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cuimín</b> (or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>) ‘son (or ‘descendant’) of <i>Cuimín</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>cam</i> ‘crooked’. There was a 7th-century abbot of Iona named <i>Cumin</i>. In Scotland, this Irish surname became confused with the Norman name.","History: A notable bearer of the Norman surname is Wilhelmus Comyn, Bishop of Durham, who came north to Scotland with King David I in 1124 and was appointed Chancellor of Scotland. He established his nephew Richard in Tynedale and Roxburghshire, and Richard also rose to be Chancellor of Scotland. The Comyn or Cumming family gained the earldoms of Buchan and Menteith and rose to be the most powerful noble family in Scotland in the century before the rise of King Robert Bruce."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Comyn was born about 1265 as the daughter of William Comyn of Lochaber. She married Sir Robert Comyn about 1291, in Elginshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1265–":"umbes 1265–Surnud","1265–Fem